    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">02</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Influences</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Mexican National Influence on Texicans</h2><ul><li>Mexican independence (1821) redefined political and cultural identity</li><li>Mexican laws and customs influenced Texican governance and society</li><li>Texicans adopted Mexican symbols and language but retained local distinctiveness</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">After Mexico’s independence from Spain, Texicans became Mexican citizens, adopting new political and cultural frameworks while maintaining unique regional traits. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican communities participated in Mexican elections and observed Mexican holidays, blending national identity with local traditions.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Discuss how Mexican national identity both integrated and diverged from Texican local culture.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overgeneralizing Texicans as simply Mexican without recognizing their hybrid identity.</p></div></div>",
