    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Source Analysis</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Interpreting Texican Letters and Diaries</h2><ul><li>Examine personal letters and diaries from Texican settlers (s10, s11).</li><li>Identify expressions of identity, loyalty, and daily challenges.</li><li>Note language use reflecting cultural blending.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary documents such as letters and diaries provide direct insight into how Texicans viewed themselves and their world, revealing complex identities and loyalties during early Texas history. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A diary entry from 1835 reveals a Texican settler’s conflicted feelings about Mexican governance and Anglo settlers encroaching on land.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a provided excerpt from a Texican letter and identify key themes about identity and allegiance.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all Texicans shared a uniform identity or political stance without considering individual perspectives.</p></div></div>",
