    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">15</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Interpretation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Field Disagreements on Texican Identity</h2><ul><li>Historians debate whether Texicans were primarily Mexican loyalists or early Texans (s16, s17).</li><li>Some argue Texicans had a distinct identity blending Mexican and Anglo influences.</li><li>Others see Texicans as transitional figures in Texas independence.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Scholars differ on how to classify Texicans, reflecting the complexity of identity in a contested frontier region during political upheaval. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s17\">[17]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> One historian emphasizes Texican loyalty to Mexico, while another highlights their role in Texas independence movements.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Compare two scholarly interpretations and identify the evidence supporting each view.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Accepting a single narrative without considering the evidence and arguments from multiple perspectives.</p></div></div>",
