      "h": "Navigating Scholarly Debates",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Scholars differ on how to classify Texicans, reflecting the complexity of identity in a contested frontier region during political upheaval.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.uta.edu; guides.library.yale.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Historians debate whether Texicans were primarily Mexican loyalists or early Texans (s16, s17).</li><li>Some argue Texicans had a distinct identity blending Mexican and Anglo influences.</li><li>Others see Texicans as transitional figures in Texas independence.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>One historian emphasizes Texican loyalty to Mexico, while another highlights their role in Texas independence movements.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Compare two scholarly interpretations and identify the evidence supporting each view.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Accepting a single narrative without considering the evidence and arguments from multiple perspectives.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.uta.edu; guides.library.yale.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s17\">[17]</sup></p>"
